# Tic-Tac-Toe game using python.

For been a good programme you need to understand what you are developing and for whom you are developing. Whenever we start writing code we should take a moment and think as a user that what a user want from my program or any program in general.So we made a list.


## Rules
*    If any of the players have filled a square then the other player and the same player cannot override that square.
*    There are only two conditions that may match will be draw or may win.
*    He player that succeeds in placing three respective marks (X or O) in a horizontal, vertical, or diagonal row wins the game



## *Structure of the programme*
In a basic tic tac toe game, we have 3*3 boxes but in our application, we can't erase that so we need something to make everything blank to play again. All the basic rules of a tic tac toe are like it's a two-player game One has X and the second player has O.They both have only one chance so after clicking once the option should change automatically. We need some logic to check who wins and  show that on screen.

### Logic for the tic-tac-toe

We need a way to put our x or o on the screen on clicking.

Let's write a function for that. We need to change the text from blank to X or O on clicking.First we write our function in simple English.

First, we check what button got clicked then change the button's text.

But writing function for every button makes our code complex. We need a function that we can use for all buttons. The clicked button should be passed in the function and the text of the button changes.


def clicked(button):
  button['text'] = 'X'

The above code works fine for our program but we need that after every click the text of the button should be different from last.

**Example:** 

First, i clicked button one and the text of button one is X so when i click on anyother button the text should be O .the change between text should  constant.


For making this work we need something to check or something which helps us to make the logic work.

To make this we can use a boolean variable if its true then the text will be O if it's false then the text will be X.And after every turn, the value should move back and forth between true and false.For this, we need to use an if else in our function and a boolean variable to change after every execution.

player = True

def clicked(button):
  global player # We are making player variable to global means we can change the variable inside as well as outside the function
  if player == False:
    button['text'] = "X"
  elif player == True:
    button['text'] == 'O'
  else:
    pass

In the above code, we write a boolean variable called player and set its default value to True. Then we start writing our program. The first line of our program was global player this global keyword allows you to modify the variable outside of the current scope. This makes us work with the player inside the function now we can change the value of the player from inside the function it's important because we need to change its value after every execution.Then we start writing our if else statement where we check the value of the player variable if it's false then the text will be X or if it's true then the text will be O. I wrote an else pass because in case both test case fails we need that our function doesn't do anything.


Now the thing how can we make to execute this function on every click?

The answer is in our Tkinter documentation when we read about buttons. We can see that we can pass a function to execute on click by just adding this in our button.

command=function

```
button_1 = Button( add this to the end of button creation command=function)
```

But wait a minute we need to pass a parameter into the function. 
 
By using lambda we can do this.So what is lamdba? lambda is an anonymous function is a function that is defined without a name. While normal functions are defined using the def keyword in Python, anonymous functions are defined using the lambda keyword. Hence, anonymous functions are also called lambda functions.But we can also pass the parameter in this while writing the parameter.If you want to learn about lambda you can just google there are a ton of resources where you can learn more about lambda but for now, we just know that we can use this to pass our button in the function



```
button_1 = Button(window, height=4, width=8, bg='grey',text='', command=lamdba:clicked(button_1)
```


But We need to make sure that we define our function before using it because python starts reading the code from top to bottom. If we define our function below the buttons then python gives us an error.

from tkinter import *
from tkinter import messagebox


# Making window
window = Tk()
window.title("Tic Tac Toe")
window.geometry("400x400")
window.resizable(False, False)



# setting player
player=False
# player labels to show player one and two options
Label(window,text="Player 1 - X").place(x=50,y=50)
Label(window,text="Player 2 - O").place(x=300,y=50)


#score variables
x_score = 0
o_score = 0
# score label to show score on the screen
Label(window,text=f"X = {x_score}").place(x=100,y=10)
Label(window,text=f"O = {o_score}").place(x=280,y=10)


# Button click function
def clicked_button(button):
    # making player global to change this inside the function
    global player
    if player==False and button['text']=='':
        # changing text
        button['text'] = 'X'
        # changing font color
        button['fg']='red'
        # changing value of player from false to true
        player=True
        check_winner()
    elif player==True and button['text']=='':
        # changing text
        button['text'] = 'O'
        # changing font color
        button['fg']='green'
        # changing value of player from true to false
        player=False
        check_winner()

# RESETING FOR NEW GAME
# list of buttons
ls_btn = [button_1,button_2, button_3, button_4, button_5, button_6, button_7,button_8, button_9]
# reset tiles
def reset():
    for i in ls_btn:
        i['text'] = ''

# reset score 
def reset_score():
    x_score = 0
    o_score = 0
    Label(window,text=f"X = {x_score}").place(x=100,y=10)
    Label(window,text=f"O = {o_score}").place(x=280,y=10)
    

# Button to reset all the button to reset
button_reset =Button(window, height=1,width=4, text='Reset', command=reset)
button_reset.place(x=10, y=10)

# Button to reset score

button_reset_score.place(x=170,y =10)
